</TABLE>
</P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H3><A NAME="23"></A>The Internet and Convergence</H3>

<H4>Packet Switching and the Internet</H4>

<P>Circuit vs. packet switching. Early days of the ARPAnet. Development
of routing protocols (TCP/IP) and network services like naming. ARPAnet
becomes the Internet, driven by the needs to integrate packet radio, satellite
networks, and the ARPAnet. Aloha Net and its influence on the development
of ethernet. Packet radio technology. Government decision to privatize the
Internet in the early 1990s. Key players include Paul Baran, Robert Taylor,
Larry Roberts, Frank Heart, Dave Walden, John McQuilan, Bob Kahn, Vint Cerf,
etc. The important role of Berkeley Unix in the development of the Internet.
Metricom service available on campus today.</P>

<H5>Readings</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <UL>
    <LI><A HREF="http://www.amdahl.com/internet/events/inet25.html">Internet
    25th Anniversary</A>
  </UL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<H4><A NAME="24"></A>The International Telecommunications Union</H4>

<P>The history of international agreements related to mail carrage across
borders. The need for standardization and international treaties to interconnect
national telegraphic systems at national borders. International treaty developments
to avoid radio interference. Regulatory environment in the United States:
FCC and the deregulation of the phone company. Convergence among data networking,
telephony, television services.</P>

<H5>Readings</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <UL>
    <LI><A HREF="http://www.silkroad.com/net-history.html">Brief History of
    Networking</A>
  </UL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

